# TUPLE
  •Tuple is also an ordered collection of multiple values with different data types in a single variable, enclosed within parenthesis().
  •It is immutable(unchangeable).
  •It also allows duplicate values.

# Eg 
details = ("Saindhavi", 20, 8.5, True)
print(details)

numbers = (10, 20, 30, 40)
print(numbers)

# Output
('Saindhavi', 20, 8.5, True)

(10, 20, 30, 40)

# Accessing
  •Each and every element in a tuple has a Index Value. 
  •The elements are accessed using the index values. 
  •Index Value starts with 0.

# Eg
fruits = ("Apple", "Banana", "Orange")
print(fruits[0])
print(fruits[1])

# Output
Apple
Banana

# Negative Indexing
  Negative Index is used to access the elements in reverse order.

# Eg
fruits = ("Apple", "Banana", "Orange")
print(fruits[-1])

# Output
Orange

# Tuple Cannot Be Modified
fruits = ("Apple", "Banana", "Orange")
fruits[1] = "Mango"

# Output
TypeError: 'tuple' object does not support item assignment

# Methods used in Tuple

•len()	
  Returns the number of elements in the tuple	
•max()	
  Returns the largest element	
•min()	
  Returns the smallest element	
•sum()	
  Returns the sum of all numeric elements	
•sorted()	
  Returns a sorted list of the tuple elements

# Eg
numbers = (30, 10, 20, 40)
print(f"Length: {len(numbers)}")
print(f"Maximum: {max(numbers)}")
print(f"Minimum: {min(numbers)}")
print(f"Sum: {sum(numbers)}")
print(f"Sorted: {sorted(numbers)}")

# Output
Length: 4
Maximum: 40
Minimum: 10
Sum: 100
Sorted: [10, 20, 30, 40]

Tuples does not support the following methods 
  •append()
  •insert()
  •reverse()
  •rempve()
  •sort()

# Passing a Tuple to a Function

def display_subjects(subjects):
    for subject in subjects:
        print(subject)

subjects = ("Maths", "Physics", "Python")
display_subjects(subjects)

# Output
Maths
Physics
Python
